# Cursor Agent Rules — OYSA RAG Chatbot

## Project Summary
This is a RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation) chatbot for the Oregon Youth Soccer Association.
It is a Next.js app hosted on Vercel, embedded via iframe on oregonyouthsoccer.org.
The corpus is a small set of operational documents and competition rules (~50 PDFs/Word docs).

## Stack — Do Not Deviate Without Asking
- **Framework**: Next.js with App Router
- **Embeddings**: OpenAI `text-embedding-3-small` (1536 dimensions) — embeddings ONLY, not generation
- **Generation**: Anthropic Claude (read from `GENERATION_MODEL` env var, current value `claude-sonnet-4-6`) — generation ONLY, not embeddings
- **Vector DB**: Pinecone serverless, index name `oysa-docs`, dimension 1536, metric cosine
- **Hosting**: Vercel serverless functions

## Shared Client Instances
Always import OpenAI, Anthropic, and Pinecone clients from `@/lib/clients.ts`.
Never instantiate these clients inline in route handlers or components.
The embed utility lives in `@/lib/embed.ts` — use `embedText()` from there.

## Environment Variables
Use only these env var names — do not introduce new ones without updating README and .env.local:
- `OPENAI_API_KEY` — OpenAI (embeddings only)
- `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` — Anthropic (generation only)
- `PINECONE_API_KEY` — Pinecone
- `PINECONE_INDEX_NAME` — defaults to "oysa-docs"
- `ADMIN_PASSWORD` — plain password for admin UI access
- `GENERATION_MODEL` - `claude-sonnet-4-6`

## Embedding Rules — Critical
- NEVER change the embedding model without flagging it explicitly. The Pinecone index dimension
  (1536) is permanently tied to `text-embedding-3-small`. Changing models requires destroying
  the index, recreating it with the new dimension, and re-ingesting all documents.
- For Pinecone retrieval, embed ONLY the latest user message (`messages.at(-1).content`).
  Do NOT embed the full conversation history for retrieval — it dilutes the query vector.
  Multi-turn context is handled entirely by Claude (see below), not by Pinecone.
- Always strip newlines before embedding: `text.replace(/\n/g, ' ')`

## Chat API Route Behavior
- Accept `{ messages: [{role, content}] }` in the POST body
- Embed only `messages.at(-1).content` for Pinecone retrieval
- Retrieve top 5 chunks from Pinecone (topK: 5)
- Pass retrieved chunks as part of the system prompt context, not as a user message
- Pass full conversation history to Claude as the messages array
- Claude model string: read from `process.env.GENERATION_MODEL` (current canonical value: `claude-sonnet-4-6`; verify at https://docs.anthropic.com)
- Max tokens for Claude response: 1024

## System Prompt for Claude — Non-Negotiable Constraints
Always include these constraints in the Claude system prompt:
1. Answer only from the provided document context
2. If the answer is not in the documents, say so clearly — never fabricate
3. Cite the source document when possible ("According to [filename]...")
4. Never invent rules, eligibility requirements, fees, dates, or registration deadlines
5. Keep answers concise and factual — this is a rules/compliance assistant

## Admin UI Rules
- Authentication: check `ADMIN_PASSWORD` env var against a submitted password. Simple POST, no sessions, no OAuth.
- The admin must be able to: upload a document, view indexed documents, delete a document
- UI must require zero technical knowledge — no jargon, no raw JSON, no CLI instructions shown
- Supported upload formats: PDF and .docx only
- On upload: extract text → chunk → embed → upsert to Pinecone with metadata

## Pinecone Namespace Strategy
Two namespaces are used. Never mix them.

- `"headers"` — one record per document, used by the admin UI to list the knowledge base
- `"production"` — one record per chunk, used by the chat pipeline for retrieval

The chat pipeline queries ONLY the `"production"` namespace.
The admin UI queries ONLY the `"headers"` namespace to build the document list.

## Document Header Record Schema
One header record is written to the `"headers"` namespace on every ingest.
Use the embedding of the first chunk as the vector value (Pinecone requires a valid vector).
ID format: `"header::{filename}"`

```javascript
{
  id: `header::${filename}`,
  values: embeddingOfFirstChunk,
  metadata: {
    type: "header",
    filename: string,          // normalized, e.g. "2024-competition-rules.pdf" — Pinecone key
    originalFilename: string,  // raw as uploaded, e.g. "2024 Competition Rules.pdf" — display only
    uploadDate: string,        // ISO 8601, e.g. "2026-04-27T14:32:00.000Z"
    fileSizeBytes: number,     // raw byte count
    fileSizeDisplay: string,   // human-readable, e.g. "278 KB"
    mimeType: string,          // "application/pdf" or "application/vnd.openxmlformats..."
    totalChunks: number,
    chunkIds: string[],        // e.g. ["2024-competition-rules.pdf::chunk::0", ...]
    uploadedBy: "admin"
  }
}
```

## Document Chunk Record Schema
One chunk record per text segment, written to the `"production"` namespace.
ID format: `"{filename}::chunk::{chunkIndex}"`

```javascript
{
  id: `${filename}::chunk::${chunkIndex}`,
  values: chunkEmbedding,       // 1536 floats from text-embedding-3-small
  metadata: {
    type: "chunk",
    filename: string,           // normalized — matches header record key
    originalFilename: string,   // raw as uploaded — returned in chat sources array
    chunkIndex: number,
    totalChunks: number,
    text: string                // original chunk text — returned at query time as context
  }
}
```

## Document Chunking Strategy
- Target chunk size: 400 tokens
- Overlap between chunks: 50 tokens
- Chunk 0's embedding is reused as the header record vector

## Listing Documents in Admin UI
Use `listPaginated()` then `fetch({ ids })` on the `"headers"` namespace.
Do NOT use a zero-vector query — cosine similarity is undefined for a zero vector and
results are unpredictable. Do NOT scan the `"production"` namespace.

The corpus is capped at ~50 documents, so a single `listPaginated()` call is sufficient.
Do not implement a pagination loop.

```javascript
const headerNs = index.namespace("headers");
const idsResponse = await headerNs.listPaginated();
const ids = (idsResponse.vectors ?? [])
  .map((v) => v.id)
  .filter((id) => typeof id === "string");
if (ids.length === 0) return { documents: [] };
const fetched = await headerNs.fetch({ ids });
const documents = Object.values(fetched.records ?? {}).map((r) => r.metadata);
```

## Deleting a Document
ID-based deletion is required. Pinecone's metadata-filtered `deleteMany` is NOT available
on the Starter (free) tier for serverless indexes — do not use `deleteMany({ filter: ... })`.

The `chunkIds` array stored in the header metadata is the source of truth for which chunk
IDs to delete. Always delete both the production chunks and the header record.

```javascript
const headerId = `header::${filename}`;
const headerNs = index.namespace("headers");

// 1. Fetch the header to get chunkIds
const fetched = await headerNs.fetch({ ids: [headerId] });
const header = (fetched.records ?? {})[headerId];
if (!header) return; // already deleted

// 2. Delete production chunks by ID
const chunkIds = header.metadata?.chunkIds ?? [];
if (chunkIds.length > 0) {
  await index.namespace("production").deleteMany({ ids: chunkIds });
}

// 3. Delete the header record
await headerNs.deleteOne({ id: headerId });
```

Leaving orphaned chunks in `"production"` after deleting a header means stale content
remains retrievable by the chat pipeline.

## Filename Normalization
Two filename fields are stored per document. Never mix them up.

- `filename` — normalized version. Produced by `normalizeFilename(raw)` in `lib/format.ts`.
  Used as the Pinecone ID prefix, in URL path segments, and for all internal operations.
  Example: `"2024-competition-rules.pdf"`.
- `originalFilename` — raw filename exactly as uploaded. Used only for display in the admin
  UI table and as the `sources` array values returned to the public chat UI.
  Example: `"2024 Competition Rules.pdf"`.

The admin DELETE endpoint URL carries `filename` (normalized) because it is the Pinecone key.
The `window.confirm` dialog and the chat source chips show `originalFilename` for readability.

## CORS / Embedding Strategy
- The app is embedded via iframe on oregonyouthsoccer.org — do NOT add CORS headers to API routes
- All fetch calls from the chat UI are same-origin (Vercel → Vercel)
- Do not implement script-tag embed patterns — iframe only

## Multi-Turn Conversation
Multi-turn conversation IS fully supported and IS a requirement. Here is how it works:

- The client maintains the full conversation history in React state (useState) as a
  `messages` array of `{ role: 'user' | 'assistant', content: string }` objects
- On every user message, the client sends the ENTIRE conversation history to /api/chat
- The API route embeds only the LATEST user message for Pinecone retrieval
- The API route passes the FULL conversation history to Claude as the messages array
- Claude uses the full history to understand follow-up questions in context
  (e.g. "what about transfer players?" understands "players" from the prior turn)
- This two-track approach means: Pinecone finds relevant docs from the current question,
  Claude answers it with awareness of everything said so far

Do not use localStorage for conversation persistence unless explicitly requested.
Do not implement server-side session storage unless explicitly requested.

## Code Style
- Prefer async/await over .then() chains
- Use early returns to avoid deep nesting
- Keep API route handlers thin — move logic into lib/ utilities
- No console.log in production paths — use console.error for caught exceptions only
- Use optional chaining and nullish coalescing freely

## What NOT to Do
- Do not use LangChain or any RAG framework — implement the pipeline directly
- Do not add authentication libraries (NextAuth, Clerk, etc.) — simple password check only
- Do not add a database (Postgres, Supabase, etc.) — Pinecone metadata is sufficient
- Do not implement streaming responses until the basic non-streaming version works
- Do not install packages without checking if the functionality already exists in the codebase
- Do not generate a .env.local file or output API key values in any form
